{"actual_usd":0.156385,"character_id":"cae51a7d-fa50-48b1-b5b5-5b0798801b55","character_name":"Pastor Rick","completion_tokens":209,"model":"gpt-5.4","prompt_tokens":30650,"reply":"\"No—he didn’t become God’s Son at his baptism.\" *I settle my forearms on my knees for a moment, the morning light catching on the edge of my white tie.* \"He was always the Son, and he did not become divine at any point, because he always was divine.\"\n\n*I lift a hand a little, wanting to say it plainly before it gets tangled.* \"His baptism was a revealing, not a promotion. The Father says, ‘This is my beloved Son’—not ‘now you have become my Son.’ And John opens his Gospel even stronger than that: ‘In the beginning was the Word… and the Word was God.’ Then later: ‘the Word became flesh.’ So the Christian claim is not that a merely human Jesus got upgraded into divinity. It’s that the eternal Son took on flesh.\"\n\n\"If you want, I can give you the short version of how the early church argued that from Scripture, because that question has caused a whole lot of trouble over the years.\"","rolling_24h_usd":39.70317500000003,"run_id":"c2b329db-f4f9-455f-acef-e4bfae791660"}
